[[ja:纒向勝山古墳]]
{{⚠️🚨COPIED from EverybodyWiki ❗❕⚠️😡😤Please respect Licence CC-BY-SA ❗}}
{{Source Wikipedia}}

{{draft}} {{Infobox ancient site| image=File:Makimuku_kohungun_aerial.jpg|coordinates=https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?language=ja&pagename=%E7%BA%92%E5%90%91%E5%8B%9D%E5%B1%B1%E5%8F%A4%E5%A2%B3&params=34_32_50.7_N_135_50_5.2_E_type:landmark_region:JP}} [[{{PAGENAME}}]] is a [[Kofun]] found on the premises of [[Makimuku ruins]]<ref name=":0">https://seaa-web.org/sites/default/files/publications/bseaa-1/BSEAA1-Rew-Styles.pdf</ref>.
The [[Makimuku ruins]], located in the vicinity of the famous [[Hashihaka Kofun]], has been pivotal in redefining the chronological understanding of the Kofun period. Two significant burial mounds from this region, namely the {{ill|Makimuku Ishizuka Kofun|lt=Makimuku Ishizuka|ja|纒向石塚古墳}} and Makimuku Katsuyama, have provided dendrochronological evidence that suggests revisions to established ceramic chronologies.<ref name=":0" />
== Dating == In the 1990s, dendrochronological studies on a wooden board from the {{ill|Makimuku Ishizuka Kofun|ja|纒向石塚古墳}} revealed a date of 177 CE. Subsequently, in 2001, wood remains from the Makimuku Katsuyama were dated between 103 and 199 CE. These findings imply construction dates around 180 CE for Makimuku Ishizuka and approximately 200 CE for Makimuku Katsuyama.<ref name=":0" />
The ceramic findings associated with these wood pieces further illuminate the chronology. For the Ishizuka and Katsuyama mounds, ceramics were dated to the Makimuku 3 New style and Furu 0 respectively. Further analysis by scholars, including ISHINO and BARNES, places the ceramic dating for both tombs around 250 to 275 CE. Interestingly, this ceramic chronology seems to be about 75 years out of synchronization with the dendroarchaeological dates.<ref name=":0" />
== Dendrochronology == {| class="wikitable" !Dates CE !Ceramic Types !Associated Kofun |- |158-188 |Makimuku 1 Shōnai 0 |Ishizuka |- |188-218 |Makimuku 2 Shōnai 1 |Katsuyama |- |218-243 |Makimuku 3 Shōnai 2/3 |Furu 0 |- |243-268 |Makimuku 4 Shōnai 3/5 |Furu 1 Hashihaka |}
==References== {{reflist}}
== Further reading == * [https://heritageofjapan.wordpress.com/yayoi-era-yields-up-rice/the-advent-of-agriculture-and-the-rice-revolution/who-was-queen-himiko/the-yamatai-puzzle-where-was-himikos-headquarters/in-the-news-hashihaka-tomb-may-be-queen-himikos/in-the-news-hokenoyama-tomb-in-nara-queen-himikos-tomb/]
