{{Short description|Ancient Japanese tomb}} {{Draft topics|east-asia}} {{AfC topic|geo}}
{{Infobox ancient site|type = [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|Zenpokoenfun]]| image=File:Makimuku_kohungun_aerial.jpg|coordinates=https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?language=ja&pagename=%E7%BA%92%E5%90%91%E5%8B%9D%E5%B1%B1%E5%8F%A4%E5%A2%B3&params=34_32_50.7_N_135_50_5.2_E_type:landmark_region:JP}} [[Makimuku Katsuyama Kofun]] is a [[Kofun]] found on the premises of [[Makimuku ruins]]<ref name=":0">https://seaa-web.org/sites/default/files/publications/bseaa-1/BSEAA1-Rew-Styles.pdf</ref>.It is a Kofun of [[Makimuku ruins]], and considered a transitional Kofun from the {{ill|Scallop Kofun|lt=scallop-type kofun|ja|帆立貝形古墳|1=Scallop Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Scallop Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Scallop Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} of earlier times to the [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|keyhole shaped Kofun]] that would dominate later.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book |last=Ki11er |first=J. Edward |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9780824862848 |title=Himiko and Japan's Elusive Chiefdom of Yamatai |date=2017-12-18 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-6284-8}}</ref>{{rp|249}}
The [[Makimuku ruins]], have been very important in providing information for new chronologies of Ancient Japan. [[:en:Hashihaka Kofun|Hashihaka Kofun]] is the most famous member of the ruins. Two significant Kofuns from this region, namely the [[:en:Makimuku Ishizuka Kofun|Makimuku Ishizuka]] and Makimuku Katsuyama, have provided dendrochronological evidence that suggests revisions to established ceramic chronologies.<ref name=":0" />
== Dating == The Kofun is dated to around 200CE, with the nearby [[:en:Makimuku Ishizuka Kofun|Makimuku Ishizuka Kofun]] being dated to around 180AD.<ref name=":03">https://seaa-web.org/sites/default/files/publications/bseaa-1/BSEAA1-Rew-Styles.pdf</ref>
It is considered a transitional Kofun from the {{ill|Scallop Kofun|lt=scallop-type kofun|ja|帆立貝形古墳|1=Scallop Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Scallop Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Scallop Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} of earlier times to the [[:en:Zenpokoenfun|keyhole shaped Kofun]] that would dominate later, so its chrronological position is notable.<ref name=":1" />{{rp|249}}
In the 1990s, a wooden board from the [[:en:Makimuku Ishizuka Kofun|Makimuku Ishizuka Kofun]] was dated to 177 CE with dendrochronology. In 2001, other wood remains from the [[:en:Makimuku Katsuyama Kofun|Makimuku Katsuyama Kofun]] were dated between 103 and 199 CE. These findings imply construction dates around 180 CE for Makimuku Ishizuka and approximately 200 CE for Makimuku Katsuyama.<ref name=":03" />
== Dendrochronology == {| class="wikitable" !Dates CE !Ceramic types !Associated Kofun |- |158-188 |Makimuku 1 Shōnai 0 |Ishizuka |- |188-218 |Makimuku 2 Shōnai 1 |Katsuyama |- |218-243 |Makimuku 3 Shōnai 2/3 |Furu 0 |- |243-268 |Makimuku 4 Shōnai 3/5 |Furu 1 Hashihaka |}
